< text>
Not quite  mediteranean cuisine to the book, lacks some basic Italian dishes, a little bit leanings towards the middle east cuisine, but overall a pretty good experience, nice place to grab a bite or to spend some time on the great small patio outside. Food is good, the menu is a little bit to diverse and confusing. Priced a little bit over moderate, but the area is getting more and more expensive. Small parking lot, but better than nothing. Decor wise...not good at all...well...fast food type,  blend, over covered in cheap vinyl misspelled  banners, nothing special since is a practical, express (in the title), not cozy type of eatery.</text>

< text>
This is a good, reliable place for authentic Lebanese food, quickly served, without losing quality. The prices are reasonable and the service is friendly. The menu has vegetarian options so anyone can eat here. There are a few tables inside and outside if you'd like to stay. The parking is tricky but there is a lot with room for several cars. Just follow the arrows on the pavement and don't try to turn around.< /text>

< Review>
I like Gabys as a chain. They have great chicken kabobs, hummus and babaghanoosh.   I really like the Leons Fattosh salad.
This location is a bit hectic.  Its convenient to me but the parking is terrible and the service is on the slow side.
Several times I have come here for togo, when I came to pickup my order they didnt have one of my sides. This didnt happen once or twice, it happened several times. Just seemed a bit of a disappointment to make the drive over to them and then they dont ahve what i just ordered on the phone.
Gabys is a good choice if you are looking for something healthy to eat. they have a large selection of healthy items. Your meals come with pita which is also nice.
I highly recommend the babaghanoosh when they have it in the store.
Probably better to park on the street if you can<//Review>

<Review>My family and I order from Gaby's on Jefferson a lot. We love them. Unfortunately for some reason the food has not held up to the standards that we have gotten used to. We always ask for extra pita and do not mind paying extra. The last 5 times (no joke) we've received 2 little pita packages TOTAL. I've stopped ordering any of the red meat items because the meat is over cooked and very dry. I don't order the chicken kafka anymore because I received an order that the meat was rotten and you could plainly smell that it was rotten. It has become a hit or miss with them and that makes me sad because we really did love them. I hope they get back to their old ways or unfortunately I don't think we will be ordering from them anymore. I hate to complain but I hope this helps to bring them back to the wonderful restaurant they once were.< /Review>< Pictures>

<gmapID>0x80c2b0a69471113d:0xf03f1fd30ea06056<//gmapID>< review>
Gaby's is exceptional. I've been frequenting this place since 2010 and it has always been great. I recommend the shawarma combo plate, any one of their pita wraps, body builder plate, rotisserie chicken, creamed spinach, grape leaves, and tabouleh. Only thing is that their menu is very specific and sometimes you can't combine certain meals & sides or substitute easily (which is the reason for the 4 stars). Besides that, this place is great to grab a quick lunch or even a decent dinner on the way. They have a ton of condiments to accommodate your food as well.  Oh, they have breakfast in the morning as well. I recommend the California omelette w/ avocado. Definitely try it if you get a chance!</review>

<Rate>5</Rate>< Review>
The casual version of Delage with creative Chef Chikara-San who is from Oita prefecture originally. Regular menu is all stable and good with reasonable price, but if you do special order well in advance you would enjoy variety of Wagyu dish, tuna head grill as we as Nakaochi scraping from huge tuna bones. Great combination of Hokkaido Uni and fresh Nakaochi, and you can make a hand role.</Review>

I love B-Dama with all my heart, been a customer of theirs since their restaurant on Piedmont Ave opened. If I could have them cook for me everyday, I'd be in heaven. The set lunches/dinners are some of the best deals around, with a generous portion of fish or other protein, a little salad, a bowl of soup, a nice serving of steamed rice, and another little side of veggies. If you manage to eat the whole thing like me, congratulations on joining the glutton's club!

I'm also a big fan of their tofu salad, with a creamy miso sesame dressing, seaweed, and a brighy hued, spicy oil that brings out a nice contrast to the coolness of the tofu and salad. Their hand rolls are made to order so everything arrives fresh, delicious, and beautiful to boot. Their udon or nabe hits the spot on a chilly day. My husband rotates his meal choice whe we come to Swan's Market, but I'm always in the mood for B-Dama!< /review>

<text>For me this is the most authentic Japanese food in Oakland. Inside Swan's Market, the B-Dama counter serves up quality dishes at affordable prices: fish collars, nabe pots, sashimi platters, chicken karaage, fish and meats grilled over traditional charcoal hibachis, and an ever-changing menu of daily special menu items, as well as a wide selection of Japanese sakes and a couple beer and wine choices. They also have several very nice bento lunch sets. If you want a more upscale setting and an intimate and amazing 7- or 8-course omakase-style meal, check out their Delage around the corner from B-Dama.</text>< pics>

0x808f80b7303c2c07:0x898fddfaa3d8ef24< /gmap_id>
<user_name>Cindy Toh</user_name>< user>
104974893909992623557<//user>
< review>
Recommended! Yummy Japanese food!!

== Food ==
Spicy Tuna roll (4/5)
Yummy! Not quite sure what are the ingredients that went into it other then the rice and spicy roll, but whatever it is, it was really good. One order gets you six pieces.

Tonkotsu (5/5)
Woo, this was super good. The external texture was not too thick and yet still has the crunch and crispness. The meat on the inside was moist and tasty, the accompanying sauce made it even more awesome.

Pork Belly (5/5)
This was an order error but a wonderful mistake. We ordered Salmon belly nigiri but somehow the server heard it as Pork Belly. We saw the chef cooking this through the glass and were drooling at it, in a way delighted that it turned out to be ours.

Cooked over charcoal, the flavour was so awesome. The smell and every bite was just so so good. It came with lettuce to wrap it in which was delicious!

== Ambience ==
This Japanese restaurant sits in a hipster marketplace that has a variety of options such as Mexican, seafood, chicken, pizza etc.

I sat by the bar table with a glass panel to watch the chef/cook in action. The hygiene and cleanliness of the restaurant does make me a less squirm-ish...... compensated by the delicious food.

I will be back! Excited to try the yummy looking udon noodles!< /review>

<text>Update: Jan 19, 2018

Wow this place is really inconsistent. My first meal was four stars, but this meal was a 1 or 2. I saw in another review that ownership has changed.

The spicy beef noodle soup was cold and not spicy despite me asking for it extra spicy and then asking again for more spice after it was served.

The pan fried noodle is actually a deep fried noodle, aka birds nest noodle which is one of my least favorite dishes.

The spicy wonton was cold not spicy and lacked the peanut flavor it had the first time.

They were also out of most vegetables.

< Review>
Nissani BROS had our car for over two months with little to no communication. They have egregious customer service, will put you on hold for unbearable amounts of time, speak to you with total disrespect, hang up on you, and make significant repairs to your car (I'm talking transmission replacement) without even notifying you.

At this point, we don't even feel comfortable driving the car they've serviced for fear that they haven't fixed what they said. There is zero reason to trust them OR Jeep.

Also, as sad as I am to say it, if you are considering a Jeep, find another brand of car (as long as it's not Fiat, Chrysler, Dodge, or RAM). FCA (Fiat Chrysler Automobiles), which owns all of these brands, is the most atrocious company out there. Search customer service ratings and complaints, and see for yourself. It is a terrible example of how a big business takes total advantage of people. Because of their inaction (on warrantied repairs, no less), we've had no option but to pay for a rental for the past 2+ months, in addition to our lease. What's more, we've spent 30+ hours on the phone trying to track down their case managers (customer service) with very little success, not to mention time spent at rental car companies, talking to insurance, etc. I can't even imagine how many people they've done this to, and how it's impacted their ability to get to work, pay their bills, or support their families.  For what it's worth, I think FCA's negligence and poor customer service could be partly why Nissani BROS is so terrible. Nissani BROS is only able to do warrantied repairs at the speed that FCA approves them and sends the parts... Well, FCA takes FOREVER to do anything and will force them to do the same repair multiple times even when it's clear there's a bigger issue. Nissani BROS is likely very accustomed to frustrated customers and have adapted a terrible attitude and poor communication/customer care as a result.

STAY AWAY.<//Review>

Customer service has no idea what they're doing.

Two days ago, I made an appointment to take care of a recall on a part on my Chrysler.  I was told they could take care of it the next day so I made an appointment.

The next day, I brought in my car.  The person I spoke with (the name on the invoice is Raidel Soto but I'm not completely sure that's who I spoke with) had no record of my having an appointment and told me that they didn't have the part I needed.  He said they should get it the next day and would call me when it arrived.

The next day (today), I called to ask if the part had come in.  I was, in the course of 10 minutes, transferred 7 times before anyone would even begin to try to answer my question, each time implying that I had been transferred to the wrong person or department.

The sixth person I spoke with (possibly David?) asked for a part number (which I provided) then said he would need to transfer me again.  The seventh at least went to the trouble of trying to look me up in the system but couldn't find me, meaning that Raidel (or whoever it was) didn't get me in the system in the first place.  Finally, he said that he would try to contact Raidel directly and placed me on hold.

After being on hold for two minutes, I heard ringing, followed by what sounded like a mumbled "Sorry, sir," followed by silence.  After sitting in silence for a couple of minutes (chatting about my frustrations with my wife next to me, including a statement that I was thinking about leaving a bad review and going elsewhere), an automated voice informed me that I had been leaving a voicemail.

Sorry, guys, you scored a zero today.<//review>

<resp>None< /resp>< text>
I had a great experience at Oakland Kia getting a new car for our family. The sales folks were helpful and informative, but not pushy. I immediately got to test drive the car I was interested in, and the person joining us on the test drive shared a lot of useful information about the car without feeling like they were desperately working towards a commission. I got a fair trade-in offer for my current car, with a break down of where that number came from.

When we decided to go ahead and make the purchase, the financing and other paperwork was put together explaining to us at each step what's happening, what we're signing and why. Zero shadiness or lack of clarity. While we were going through that, other folks detailed the car and filled it up with gas.

In addition to having a great experience dealing with folks at Oakland Kia, we are absolutely loving our new Niro. Overall, I couldn't be happier.< /text>
